{{distinguish|text=[[Altanochir (1882-1949)]]<!-- 阿勒坦鄂齐尔 -->, deputy head of Yeke-juu League, or [[Altanochir (born 1929)]]<!-- 阿拉坦敖其尔 -->, former deputy chairman of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region}}
[[File:Jin Yongchang.jpg|thumb|right|Altanochir as pictured in a 1941 Japanese "who's who" bibliographical dictionary of China<ref name="AsahiShimbun"/>]]
'''Altanochir''' (1887–?) was an [[Inner Mongolia]]n politician under the [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]] and the [[Mengjiang]] government.<ref name="AsahiShimbun">{{harvnb|Asahi Shimbun|1941}}</ref>
==Names== Historical sources refer to him by a variety of names: *Altanochir or Altan Ochir ({{zh|c=阿拉坦鄂齊爾|p=Ālātǎnèqíěr}}), his [[Mongolian name]]<ref>In [[Mongolian Cyrillic alphabet|Mongolian Cyrillic]] spelling, Алтан-Очир</ref> *Altanvachir or Altan Vachir ({{zh|c=阿勒唐瓦齊爾 or 阿勒唐瓦其爾|p=Ālētángwǎqíěr}}), an earlier transcription of his Mongolian name<ref name="AsahiShimbun"/> *Chin Yung-chang ({{zh|c=金永昌|p=Jīn Yǒngchāng}}), his [[Chinese name]]<ref name="Jin">{{harvnb|Jin|2008|p=64}}</ref>
==Career== When Altanochir was in his youth, he was one of a small number of [[Mongolians in Japan#Students|Mongolian students sent to Japan]] under the sponsorship of Prince [[Gungsangnorbu]] of Right [[Harqin Banner]].<ref name="Li">{{harvnb|Li|Cribb|2003|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=DGQMKex16AsC&pg=PA92 92]}}</ref> He would go on to become a member of the [[Inner Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]].<ref name="Li"/> He would go on to join the [[Mengjiang]] government in 1937, and rose to the position of Minister of Communications in 1939.<ref name="AsahiShimbun"/> He also served as first head of the Mongolian Cultural Centre (蒙古文化館) in [[Hohhot]]. In September 1939, he was succeeded by Idchin (伊德欽) in that position, and became rector of the Mongolian Academy (蒙古學院).<ref name="Jin">{{harvnb|Jin|2008|p=64}}</ref>
Altanochir was known to have remained in [[mainland China]] following the establishment of the [[People's Republic of China]] in 1949, but his fate after that point is unknown.<ref>{{harvnb|Atwood|2000|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GHAUAQAAIAAJ&q=%2B%22altan+ochir%22 97]}}</ref> His son Togtakhu (托克托琥) was active in the [[Kuomintang]], and went on to teach at the [[Mongolian and Tibetan School]] in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{harvnb|Atwood|1992|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=L94KAQAAMAAJ&q=%2B%22altan+ochir%22 37]}}</ref>
