'''Bohemond II''' (1107/1108 – February 1130) was [[Prince of Taranto]] from 1111 to 1128 and [[Prince of Antioch]] from 1111/1119 to 1130. He was the son of [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond I]], who in 1108 was forced to submit to the authority of the [[Byzantine Empire]] in the [[Treaty of Devol]]. Three years later, the infant Bohemond inherited the Principality of Taranto under the guardianship of his mother, [[Constance of France, Princess of Antioch|Constance of France]]. The [[Principality of Antioch]] was administered by his father's nephew, [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred]], until 1111. Tancred's cousin, [[Roger of Salerno]], managed the principality from 1111 to 1119. After Roger died in the [[Battle of Ager Sanguinis|Battle of the Field of Blood]], [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem]] took over the administration of Antioch. However, he did acknowledge Bohemond's right to personally rule the principality upon reaching the age of majority.

Bohemond came to Antioch in autumn 1126. He launched successful military campaigns against the nearby Moslem rulers, but his conflict with [[Joscelin I of Courtenay]] enabled [[Imad ad-Din Zengi]] to secure [[Mosul]] and [[Aleppo]]. Meanwhile, [[Roger II of Sicily]] occupied the Principality of Taranto in 1128. Bohemond died fighting against [[Danishmend]] [[Emir Gazi Gümüshtigin]] during a military campaign against [[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Cilician Armenia]], and Gümüshtigin sent Bohemond's [[embalmed]] head to the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid Caliph]].

== Early life ==

Bohemond II was the son of Bohemond I, Prince of Taranto and Antioch, and Constance of France.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=125, Appendix III (Genealogical tree No. 2.)}} He was born in 1107 or 1108.{{sfn|Houben|2002|p=31}}<ref>{{Cite web |author=The Editors of Encyclopædia Britannica |title=Bohemond II Prince of Antioch |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.  |year=2016 |url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Bohemond-II |access-date=3 May 2016}}</ref> In 1104, Bohemond I returned to Europe to seek military assistance against the Byzantine Empire and left his nephew Tancred in Syria to administer Antioch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=83}} Two charters show that Tancred styled himself "prince of Antioch" in 1108.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=137}} In September of that year, Bohemond I was forced to sign the Treaty of Devol, which authorized the Byzantine Empire to annex the Principality of Antioch upon his death.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=137–138}}

Bohemond I died in Apulia in 1111. Bohemond II was still a minor,{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=51}} so his mother took charge of the government of Taranto.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=304}} The Byzantine Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]] sent envoys to Tancred to demand control of Antioch, but Tancred refused to obey and continued to govern the principality.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=138}} Tancred died in 1112 and bequeathed Antioch to his sister's son, Roger of Salerno.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=103}}{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=124}}

Roger's legal status during his rule in Antioch is uncertain.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=139}} According to [[William of Tyre]], Tancred made Roger his successor "with the understanding that, at the demand of Bohemond or his heirs, he should not refuse to return it," suggesting that Roger was simply regent for the child Bohemond.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=141–142}} Roger adopted the title of prince, which implies that he regarded himself the ruler of Antioch in his own right.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=139}}{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=126}} The contemporaneous [[Fulcher of Chartres]] accused Roger of depriving of "his inheritence his own lord, the son of Bohemond [I], then living in Apulia with his mother."{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=141}} Charters issued in Bohemond's Italian domains between 1117 and 1119 emphasized that he was the son of the prince of Antioch, but did not style him prince.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=142}}

After Roger and most Antiochene noblemen perished in the Battle of the Field of Blood on 28 June 1119, Baldwin II of Jerusalem hurried to Syria to save Antioch from [[Ilghazi]], the [[Artuqids|Artuqid]] ruler of [[Mardin]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=123–124}}{{sfn|Runciman|1989|pp=149, 152}} The notables of Antioch proclaimed Baldwin ruler of Antioch, but they emphasized that Antioch was Bohemond's "rightful inheritance," according to [[Walter the Chancellor]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=141}}{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=152}} Baldwin promised to cede Antioch to Bohemond if Bohemond came to the principality.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=141}} Those who were present at the meeting agreed that Bohemond should marry Baldwin's daughter, [[Alice of Antioch|Alice]].{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=152}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=146}} They also decreed that Bohemond would not be entitled to reclaim grants made during his absence from the principality.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=146}}

Baldwin II was captured in 1123,{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=419}} and the burghers of Antioch sent envoys to Bohemond, urging him to come to his principality.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=428}} Bohemond reached the age of majority at the age of 16.{{sfn|Houben|2002|p=31}} According to William of Tyre, he made an agreement with [[William II, Duke of Apulia]], stipulating that the one who first died without issue was to will his principality to the other; however, the reliability of William's report is suspect.{{sfn|Houben|2002|p=43}}{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=307}} [[Alexander of Telese]] recorded that before leaving for Syria, Bohemond entrusted his Italian domains to the Holy See, but [[Romuald of Salerno]] said that he made [[Alexander, Count of Conversano]], the overseer of those lands.{{sfn|Houben|2002|p=43}}{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}} Bohemond sailed from Otranto with a fleet of twenty-four ships in September 1126.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=176}}

== Prince of Antioch ==

[[File:Map Crusader states 1135-en.svg|thumb|right|The [[crusader states]] around 1135]]

Bohemond landed at the port of [[St Symeon|St. Symeon]] in the Principality of Antioch in October or November.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=146}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=428}} He went to Antioch to meet Baldwin II of Jerusalem, who subsequently ceded Antioch to him.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=176}} Bohemond was officially installed as prince in Baldwin's presence.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=147}}

[[Matthew of Edessa]] portrayed Bohemond as "a forceful character and great power."{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=147}} Badr ad-Daulah captured [[Kafartab]] shortly after Bohemond's arrival, but Bohemond quickly recaptured the fortress in early 1127.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=176}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=147}} According to historian [[Steven Runciman]], Bohemond's attack against the [[Munqidhites]] of [[Shaizar]], which was recorded by Usama ibn Munqidh, also occurred during this period.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=176}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=147}}

Bohemond came into conflict with [[Joscelin I of Edessa]] in 1127,{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=127}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=428}} although sources do not reveal the reason behind the enmity of the two Christian rulers.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=127}} According to Runciman, Joscelin seized former Antiochene territories from Il-Bursuqi, governor of Mosul. Furthermore, Bohemond refused to cede [[Azaz]] to Joscelin, despite the fact that Roger of Salerno promised it to Joscelin as the dowry of his second wife, Maria of Salerno.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=181}} Taking advantage of Bohemond's absence due to a campaign, Joscelin invaded Antioch with the assistance of Turkish mercenaries, plundering the villages along the frontier.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=181}}

[[Bernard of Valence]], [[Latin Patriarch of Antioch]], imposed an [[interdict]] on the [[County of Edessa]].{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=181}} Baldwin II of Jerusalem hurried to Syria to mediate between Bohemond and Joscelin in early 1128.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=428}}{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=181}} Joscelin, who had become seriously ill, agreed to restore the property to Bohemond and to do homage to him.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|pp=428–429}} However, the conflict between Bohemond and Joscelin enabled Imad ad-Din Zengi, Il-Bursuqi's successor as governor of Mosul, to seize Aleppo without resistance on 28 June 1128.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|pp=181–182}}

Meanwhile, Bohemond's cousin, William II of Apulia, had died without issue on 25 July 1127.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=307}} [[Pope Honorius II]] tried to prevent Roger II of Sicily (the cousin of both William and Bohemond) from seizing Apulia, but Roger did not obey him.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}} In May 1128, he invaded Bohemond's Italian principality,{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}} capturing [[Taranto]], [[Otranto]] and [[Brindisi]] without resistance.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}} He completed the conquest of the whole principality around 15 June.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}}

Taking advantage of the disputes between the [[Assassins]] and [[Taj al-Muluk Buri]], atabeg of Damascus, Baldwin II of Jerusalem invaded Damascene territory and laid siege to [[Banias]] in November 1129.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=180}} Bohemond and Joscelin joined Baldwin, but a heavy rainfall forced the crusaders to abandon the siege.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=180}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=127}}

Bohemond decided to recover [[Anazarbus]] and other territories which had been lost to the Cilician Armenia.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=182}} He invaded Cilicia in February 1130, traveling along the [[Ceyhan River]].{{sfn|Runciman|1989|pp=182–183}} [[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leo I of Cilicia]] sought assistance from the Danishmend Emir Gazi Gümüshtigin who made a surprise attack on Bohemond's army.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=183}} Bohemond and his soldiers were massacred in the battle.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=431}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=152}} According to Michael the Syrian, the Turks killed Bohemond because they did not recognize him; had they recognized him, they would have saved him so they could demand a ransom from him.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=395}} Gümüshtigin had Bohemond's head embalmed and sent to [[Al-Mustarshid]], the Abbasid Caliph.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=183}}

