Bohemond's wife, Alice, was the second daughter of Baldwin II of Jerusalem and Morphia of Melitene.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=176, Appendix III (Genealogical tree No. 1.)}} Their only child, [[Constance of Antioch|Constance]], was two when Bohemond died in 1130.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=184}} Alice tried to secure the regency for Constance for herself, but the Antiochene noblemen preferred her father, Baldwin II of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Runciman|1989|p=184}} After Bohemond's death, Roger II of Sicily laid claim to Antioch, but he could never assert it against Constance.{{sfn|Houben|2002|pp=44, 78}}

