===Quadruplets (4)=== * The Smith quadruplets, born 1750 in [[Kinsale]], a fisherman's wife.<ref>{{cite book |last=Aldwell |first=Alexander |url=http://www.corkpastandpresent.ie/places/streetandtradedirectories/1844-5aldwellscountycitypogeneraldirectory/1844-5pages132to191/GeneralDirectory1844Pages156%20to%20161.pdf |title=Cork Post Office General Directory, 1884-5 |publisher=F. Jackson |page=156 |quote=Jane Smith, a fisherman's wife in Kinsale, had four boys at a birth}}</ref> * Dominica, 1790: According to ''The Times'', a Dr. Giuseppe of Dominica reported that an unnamed Afro-Dominican woman (enslaved servant) living on the estate of Thomas Jemmitt gave birth to four girls, three of them almost eighteen hours after the first was born. All survived birth.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Times (London, England)|issue=1636|date=2 March 1790}}</ref> * The Gehri quadruplets (born September 26, 1880, in [[Switzerland]]) were the first recorded to have survived to adulthood. There were two boys (Oskar and Arthur) and two girls (Bertha and Rosa).<ref>{{cite web|last=Samson |first=Jennifer |url=http://www3.telus.net/tyee/multiples/quadruplets.html |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091015163545/http://www3.telus.net/tyee/multiples/quadruplets.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=October 15, 2009 |title=Quadruplets |publisher=Facts About Multiples |accessdate=January 29, 2013 }}</ref> * The Page quadruplets (born January 8, 1890, in [[Redwater, Texas]]) were the first recorded quadruplets born in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.redwatertexas.com/history.html|title=City of Redwater, Texas|last=|first=|date=|website=Redwater Texas|access-date=February 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Leon|first=J.|date=1891|title=Remarkable Fecundity|url=https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=e+t+page+quadruplets&sig=svPcl9uqkkJupDDylhr%20OBHRcLAs&id=IsxXAAAAMAAJ&ots=4RSR66fXlR&output=text|journal=Columbus Medical Journal|volume=9|pages=19–23|via=}}</ref> * The Keys quadruplets (born June 4, 1915, in [[Hollis, Oklahoma]]) were the first same-sex quadruplets known to survive to adulthood. They attended [[Baylor University]] on scholarships and graduated in 1937. Roberta Keys Torn, the last surviving sister, died at 96 years in August 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/houstonchronicle/obituary.aspx?n=roberta-keys-torn&pid=153190186&fhid=6290 |title=Roberta Keys Torn Obituary |work=Houston Chronicle |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> * The Mahaney quadruplets (born December 25, 1923, in [[St John, New Brunswick]]) were the first quadruplets born in Canada known to survive to adulthood. <ref>[http://archive.macleans.ca/article/1927/12/1/the-only-living-quadruplets Macleans magazine 1927/12/1 The Only Living Quadruplets] From an article in the St. John Telegraph Journal dated 28 December, 1923 quoting a response from Dr. H. S. Beland, Canadian Minister of Health.</ref> * The Johnson quadruplets (born in 1935 in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand) were the first surviving set of quadruplets in [[Australasia]].<ref>Sell, Bronwyn. (May 26, 2007). "[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/6/story.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10441605&pnum=0 Plunket, a caring society]." ''The New Zealand Herald.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Miles quadruplets (born on November 28, [[1935]] in [[St Neots]], [[United Kingdom]]) are the oldest living quadruplets in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/update/2015-11-29/worlds-oldest-surving-quads-celeberate-their-80th/|title=World's oldest surviving quads celebrate their 80th|work=itv.com|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> * The Badgett quadruplets (born February 1, 1939, in [[Galveston, Texas]]) were the second surviving set of quadruplets in the United States. The four girls, Geraldine, Joan, Jeanette, and Joyce, were minor celebrities in the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name="badgett">{{cite news |url=http://lowery.tamu.edu/personal/ballhigh/news.htm |title=Badgett Quadruplet of Galveston dies |work=Houston Chronicle |date=November 9, 2002 |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> * [[The Fultz Sisters|The Fultz quadruplets]] (born May 23, 1946, in [[Rockingham County, North Carolina|Rockingham County]], [[North Carolina]]) were the first identical African-American quadruplets on record.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ahearn |first=Lorraine |url=http://mm.news-record.com/legacy/indepth/fultz/day1/day1.html |title=And then there was one |work=The News & Record |date=August 4, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228045536/http://mm.news-record.com/legacy/indepth/fultz/day1/day1.html |archivedate=December 28, 2007}}</ref> * The Sara quadruplets (born August 17, 1950, in [[Bellingen, New South Wales]]) were the first surviving quadruplets in Australia. There were two boys, Mark and Philip, and two girls, Alison and Judith.<ref>{{cite news |last=McLagan |first=Greg |url=http://www.bellingencourier.com.au/news/local/news/general/birthing-at-bellinger-river-district-hospital/1474042.aspx |title=Birthing at Bellingen River District Hospital |work=Courier-Sun |location=Bellingen, NSW |date=March 31, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305205326/http://www.bellingencourier.com.au/news/local/news/general/birthing-at-bellinger-river-district-hospital/1474042.aspx |archivedate=March 5, 2012}}</ref> * The Alexander quadruplets (born September 2, 1967, in [[Auckland]], New Zealand) were the first set of identical quadruplets born in New Zealand.<ref>Harrison, Anna (October 4, 2007). "[https://archive.is/20120910233454/http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/4225597a22695.html Quads are still bubbling]". Stuff.co.nz. Retrieved October 5, 2007.</ref> * The Steeves quadruplets (Carrie Dawn, Jennie Lee, Mary Beth, and Patty Ann, born December 17, 1982, in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]]) were the first identical set of quadruplets to be born in Canada.<ref>Fortney, Valerie (August 18, 2007). "[http://www.canada.com/topics/bodyandhealth/story.html?id=20104de2-3ab1-48f3-93a7-85f13a80bc76&p=3 Steeves quadruplets all grown up] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123065332/http://www.canada.com/topics/bodyandhealth/story.html?id=20104de2-3ab1-48f3-93a7-85f13a80bc76&p=3 |date=November 23, 2007 }}". ''The Calgary Herald''. Retrieved October 15, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070825/quads_attention_070825/20070825?hub=Canada Quads will get lifetime of attention: grown quads]". CTV News. August 25, 2007. Retrieved October 15, 2007.</ref> * The Durst quadruplets (Calli, Kendra, Megan, and Sarah) are identical quadruplets born February 10, 1993, in [[Robbinsdale, Minnesota]].<ref>Levy, Paul (August 18, 2007). "[http://www.startribune.com/389/story/1366502.html The Durst Quadruplets: Four at fourteen] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113153956/http://www.startribune.com/389/story/1366502.html |date=November 13, 2007 }}". ''Star Tribune''. Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> They appeared on the reality television series ''[[Four of a Kind (TV series)|Four of a Kind]]''. * The [[Brino quadruplets]] (born September 21, 1998, in [[Woodland Hills, California]]) played the twins [[List of 7th Heaven characters#Sam and David Camden|Sam and David Camden]] on the television series ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''. When they all started to look different, the only girl, Myrinda, stopped appearing on the show. Only Nikolas and Lorenzo starred on the show until the series ended in 2007.<ref>"[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0109673/bio Lorenzo Brino]". The Internet Movie Database. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Mathias quadruplets (born February 16, 2000, in [[Lexington, South Carolina]]) are Grace, Emily, Mary Claire, and Anna. A home-movie of the girls laughing in unison was featured on ''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]'' and won them over $250,000 as a result.<ref>Pepin, Rebecca (May 5, 2004). "[http://wistv.com/global/story.asp?s=1844301&ClientType=Printable Mathias quads at 4-years-old]". WISTV. Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref><ref>Segal, Nancy L. (2006). "SuperQuads: A Day in the Life". ''Twin Research and Human Genetics'' '''9'''(4): 609–614. Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> The girls were featured in three 1-hour episodes of a documentary called "Super Quads" in the Discovery Health Channel. * The Aberdeen / Edwards quadruplets (born November 7, 2006, in [[San Juan, Trinidad and Tobago]]) are four girls, born to Lystra Aberdeen (aged 27 and mother to a 10-year-old girl, an 8-year-old boy, and a 4-year-old boy) and her common-law husband Anderson Edwards (aged 33). This was the first confirmed case in Trinidad.<ref>{{cite news |last=Matroo |first=Carol |url=http://legacy.guardian.co.tt/archives/2006-11-09/news1.html |title=Mom gives birth to quadruplets: Four bouncing baby girls! |work=The Trinidad Guardian |date=November 9, 2006 |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> * The Yarns quadruplets were featured on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' with [[Jay Leno]], featuring [[John Travolta]] (Season 11, Episode 97) on their birthday, February 20, 2003. They are Rhys, Trey, Chase, and Tiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.preemiecare.org/rsv_bios.htm|title=PreemieCare -RSV (Respiratory syncytial virus) Awareness & Prevention|work=preemiecare.org|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://vids.tv/the-tonight-show-with-jay-leno/tv/season-11/episode-161 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130915105735/http://vids.tv/the-tonight-show-with-jay-leno/tv/season-11/episode-161 |archive-date=2013-09-15 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://staging.followmy.tv/episodes/746277/The_Tonight_Show_with_Jay_Leno/11x161/John_Travolta_Yarns_Quadruplets_Interpol |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-09-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312213324/http://staging.followmy.tv/episodes/746277/The_Tonight_Show_with_Jay_Leno/11x161/John_Travolta_Yarns_Quadruplets_Interpol |archivedate=2014-03-12 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seplis.com/the-tonight-show-with-jay-leno/episode/john-travolta-yarns-quadruplets-interpol/3759535/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-09-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312224635/http://www.seplis.com/the-tonight-show-with-jay-leno/episode/john-travolta-yarns-quadruplets-interpol/3759535/ |archivedate=2014-03-12 |df= }}</ref> * Adhiti, Aakrithi, Akshathy and Aapthi are quadruplets born in Chennai, Tamil Nadu. They appeared in the Tamil film ''[[Enna Satham Indha Neram]]'' (2014).<ref name="hindu">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/shooting-with-quadruplets/article6085415.ece | title=Shooting with quadruplets | work=The Hindu | accessdate=12 October 2015|author = Udhav Naig|date = 5 June 2014}}</ref>
===Quintuplets (5)=== * The Lyon quintuplets (born April 29, 1896) were the first American quintuplets who were all born alive. The last survivor died on May 14, 1896.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl = https://archive.today/20180906200158/http://www.triggcunninghamfamily.com/Lyon-Quintuplets.htm|archivedate = 2018-09-06|deadurl = no|url = http://www.triggcunninghamfamily.com/Lyon-Quintuplets.htm|title = The Lyon Quintuplets|work = The Trigg Cunningham Family Website|access-date = 2018-09-06|df = }}</ref>
[[File:Dionnequints1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Dionne quintuplets|Dionne sisters]] January 21, 1935 with then-[[Premier of Ontario]] [[Mitchell Hepburn]]]] * The [[Dionne quintuplets]] (born May 28, 1934, near [[Corbeil, Ontario]], Canada) were the first quintuplets known to survive infancy. The five girls (Yvonne, Annette, Cecile, Emilie and Marie) were also the only set of identical quintuplets known to live into adulthood.<ref>Wright, Cynthia. (1994). [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3683/is_199401/ai_n8716816 They Were Five: The Dionne Quintuplets Revisited] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213234442/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3683/is_199401/ai_n8716816 |date=2009-02-13 }}. ''Journal of Canadian Studies, 29 (4),'', 5-14. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Fischer quintuplets (born September 14, 1963, in [[Aberdeen, South Dakota]]) were the first known surviving set of American quintuplets. They consisted of one boy and four girls.<ref>"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,875191,00.html The Pride of Aberdeen]." (September 27, 1963). ''Time.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> 3 of the 4 girls are identical: Magdalene, Margaret, and Catherine.<ref>"[http://img690.imageshack.us/img690/7397/fischerzygoty.jpg Diagram of combination] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720024610/http://img690.imageshack.us/img690/7397/fischerzygoty.jpg |date=July 20, 2011 }}".</ref> * The Lawson quintuplets (born July 27, 1965, in [[Auckland]], New Zealand) were the first set of surviving quintuplets conceived through the use of [[fertility medication]] and are the only known New Zealand quintuplets:<ref name="whalen1">Whalen, J. (January 21, 2005). "[http://www.whalenquintuplets.com/quintfacts.htm Quintuplet Facts] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819232837/http://www.whalenquintuplets.com/quintfacts.htm |date=August 19, 2007 }}." Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> They are one boy (Samuel) and four girls (Deborah, Lisa, Shirlene and Selina).<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/western-leader/2848475/Quins-gran-hits-100 |title= Quins' gran hits 100 |first= Carly |last= Tawhiao |publisher= Western Leader (via [[Stuff.co.nz]]) |date= 10 September 2009 |accessdate= 17 November 2013}}</ref> * The Braham quintuplets (born 31 December 1967) were the first quintuplets to be born in Australia. They were conceived naturally<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whalenquintuplets.com/quintfacts.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819232837/http://www.whalenquintuplets.com/quintfacts.htm |archivedate=2007-08-19 |df= }}</ref> and born to Pat and Roger Braham of Tenterfield, New South Wales. In birth order they were Annabel Dorothy, Richard Gibson, Faith Elizabeth, Caroline, and Geoffrey Raymond. Geoffrey died at 4 days old; the others are still living.<ref>{{cite news|work = The Age|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19800225&id=V_VUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aJIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4651,4817496|title = Quins brought big changes|date = 25 February 1980|last = Murphy|first = Damien|location = Melbourne|page = 5}}</ref> * The Hanson quintuplets (born November 13, 1969, in [[London]]) were the first set to survive in the [[United Kingdom]], as well as the second surviving set of all-girl quintuplets after the Dionne quintuplets.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/13/newsid_3156000/3156050.stm 1969: They were born at London hospital]." (n.d.). ''[[On This Day]].'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref> * The [[Kienast quintuplets]] (born February 24, 1970, in Liberty Corners, New Jersey) were the first surviving set of American quintuplets conceived through fertility medication.<ref>Warren, Larkin. (May 1, 2001). "[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-10882822_ITM The Kienast quints all grown up]." ''Good Housekeeping.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref><ref>Dowd, Maureen. (March 5, 1984). "[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9C05E0DE1539F936A35750C0A962948260 Quintuplets' Father Lost Struggle in the Limelight]." ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> * The Rychert quintuplets (born May 15, 1971, in [[Gdańsk]]) were the first surviving set born in [[Poland]].<ref>"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YdglAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2vMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=448,1796347&dq=rychert+quintuplets].</ref> * The Brunner quintuplets (born June 9, 1978, in [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]) were the first surviving set born in [[France]]. Marc, Luc, Gilles, Maud, and Anne were nicknamed "quintuplés Paris Match," and clothed by designer Pierre Cardin, in 17 articles written from 1978 to 1984.<ref>1st Christmas for "quintuplés Paris match" {{cite web|url=http://images.chapitre.com/ima2/big1/562/6975562.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708135056/http://images.chapitre.com/ima2/big1/562/6975562.jpg |archivedate=2011-07-08 |df= }} Paris Match 1544</ref> For each article, they were clothed by the couturier Pierre Cardin. * The Granata quintuplets (born June 1, 1981, in Toledo, Ohio) were three boys and two girls conceived through the use of [[fertility medication]] and born at 28 weeks to Janice and George Granata. They were named (in birth order) Britton, Nathan, Amanda, Heather, and Eric. Britton died of lung failure on June&nbsp;3, 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1981/07/07/nyregion/notes-on-people-geologist-is-introduced-to-life-sciences.html |title = Geologist is Introduced to Life Sciences|work = New York Times|subscription = yes|last1=Bird|first1= David|last2=Krebs|first2 =Albin}}</ref> In 1983, the surviving four appeared with [[Oprah Winfrey]] on her show, ''People are Talking'', along with their mother and their older sister Jenny.<ref>"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwRVlFO6-hI Granata Quints with Oprah on YouTube]"</ref> At age 15, the four appeared on ''[[The Jenny Jones Show]]''. * The Gaither quintuplets (born August 3, 1983, in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]) were the first surviving African-American quintuplets and were one of only three naturally-conceived American sets in 1983.<ref>"[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_21_99/ai_91474889 Nation's first Black Quints, now 17, attend high school prom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123091548/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_21_99/ai_91474889 |date=2007-11-23 }}." (May 7, 2001). ''Jet.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref><ref>Jones, Lisa C. (October 1993). "[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_n12_v48/ai_13275725 The Gaither quints grow up - quintuplets' tenth birthday] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123090634/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_n12_v48/ai_13275725 |date=2007-11-23 }}." ''Ebony.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2001/04/16/loc_at_17_indiana.html At 17, Indiana quintuplets back in spotlight at prom]." (April 16, 2001). ''The Enquirer.'' Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> * The Al-Ghamdi quintuplets (born February 2, 1988, in [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]]) were the first set to be born in Saudi Arabia. The 5 boys were born to Salha and Saeed Al-Ghamdi.<ref>Hatrash, Hasan. (April 12, 2007). "[http://www.arabnews.com/?page=21&section=0&article=94889&d=13&m=4&y=2007 Quintuplets Eyeing Scholarships to Fulfill Dreams]." ''Arab News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Nur Adlan quintuplets were born in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]] on May 20, 1996. The three girls and two boys were the first set of Malaysian quintuplets to survive infancy.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19970520&id=6vxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GRUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5098,4177491&hl=ms|title =Quintuplets celebrate their first birthday|work = New Straits Times|last = John|first = Elizabeth|date = 21 May 1997|location = Malaysia}}</ref> * The Cassidy quintuplets were born in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]] on August 16, 2001, to Veronica and Kevin Cassidy of [[Wexford]]. The three boys (Conor James, Cian Richard, and Rory Kevin) and two girls (Amy Dorothy and Dearbhail Mary) were the first quintuplets to be born in Ireland.<ref>Cassidy, John. (August 26, 2001). "[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20010826/ai_n14532867 I only got to hold Conor for a minute but I was on cloud nine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123070849/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20010826/ai_n14532867 |date=2007-11-23 }}." ''Sunday Mirror.'' Retrieved June 27, 2007.</ref><ref>Ring, Evelyn. (September 01, 2001). "[http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/09/01/story11711.asp Mother confident over well-being of quintuplets] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929145811/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/09/01/story11711.asp |date=September 29, 2007 }}." ''Irish Examiner.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>Furlong, Brendan. (September 01 2005). "[http://www.independent.ie/national-news/the-nanny-state-turns-nasty-now-famous-5-are-four-238301.html The nanny state turns nasty now Famous 5 are four]." ''Independent.ie.''. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Gonzalez-Moreno quintuplets were born in Phoenix, Arizona on April 26, 2005, to Luisa Gonzalez and Enrique Moreno via surrogate mother, Teresa Anderson. The five boys are the first set of quintuplets born via surrogate. The boys, in order of birth, are; Enrique, Jorge, Gabriel, Javier, Victor and weighed between 3&nbsp;lb 7oz and 3&nbsp;lb 15oz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/04/27/surrogate-mother-has-quintuplets/|title=Surrogate Mother Has Quintuplets|work=Fox News|date = 27 April 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/a-13-2005-04-28-voa32-67526717/387053.html|title=Quintuplets Born to Surrogate Mother|work=VOA|date= 29 October 2009}}</ref> * The Wilkinson quintuplets (born July 31, 2007, in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]) were born to Jayson and Rachelle Wilkinson of [[Cedar Park, Texas]]. The three girls (Kassidy, Kaydence, and Kyndall) and two boys (Rustin and Ryder) hold the record for the highest combined birth weight of a set of quintuplets at 21&nbsp;lb (9.52&nbsp;kg).<ref>"[http://www.bannerhealth.com/About+Us/News+Center/Press+Releases/Texas+couple+give+birth+to+record-setting+quintuplets+at+Banner+Good+Samaritan.htm Texas couple give birth to record-setting quintuplets at Banner Good Samaritan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028152249/http://www.bannerhealth.com/About%2BUs/News%2BCenter/Press%2BReleases/Texas%2Bcouple%2Bgive%2Bbirth%2Bto%2Brecord-setting%2Bquintuplets%2Bat%2BBanner%2BGood%2BSamaritan.htm |date=October 28, 2007 }}." (July 31, 2007). Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> * The Artamkin quintuplets were born in Oxford, England on November 10, 2007, to Dimitri and Varvara Artamkin via Cesarean section.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1569390/First-quintuplets-born-in-Britain-for-10-years.html|title=First quintuplets born in Britain for 10 years|author=Rebecca Smith, Medical Editor|date=15 November 2007|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/news/russian-quintuplets-born-in-the-uk-doing-well/|title=Russian Quintuplets born in the UK doing well|work=RT International}}</ref> They were the first set of quintuplets born to Russian parents.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} * The Jones quintuplets (born January 16, 2009, in [[Austin, Texas]]) were four girls and one boy born to Ethan and Casey Jones. In order of birth, they are Brooklyn Faith, Britton Grace, Jack William, Lila Addison, and Ryan Elizabeth. They have an older sister Eliot McKenna, who was four at the time of their birth. All six children were conceived through fertility treatments of [[intrauterine insemination]] (IUI) and a sperm donor when the couple learned Ethan had an extremely low sperm count. The same donor was used for Eliot and the quintuplets. The Jones quintuplets and their family had a show on [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] called ''[[Quints by Surprise]]'' that premiered on August 30, 2010. * The Kroščen quintuplets were born in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]] on June 2, 2013, to Alexandra Kiňová and Antonín Kroščen of [[Milovice (Nymburk District)|Milovice]]. The four boys (Michael, Deniel, Martin, and Alex) and one girl (Tereza) were the first recorded quintuplets to be born in the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/02/czech-republic-first-quintuplets-alexandra-kinova_n_3375134.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Mom Gives Birth To Czech Republic's First Quintuplets | date=June 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/real-life-stories/alexandra-kinova-mum-expecting-quintuplets-1923010|title=Alexandra Kinova: Mum expecting quintuplets without using IVF at odds of 50 million to one|author=Steve White|date=30 May 2013|work=mirror}}</ref> They have one older brother, Antonio. * The Busby quintuplets were born on April 8, 2015, in Houston, Texas, to Adam and Danielle Busby. The five girls (Ava Lane, Olivia Marie, Hazel Grace, Parker Kate, and Riley Paige) are the first set of all female quintuplets born in the United States. Ava and Olivia are identical twins. They have an older sister, Blayke. The Busby quintuplets and their family have a show on [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] called ''[[Outdaughtered]]'' that premiered on May 10, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2015/04/15/texas-woman-gives-birth-to-first-set-of-all-girl-quintuplets-in-u-s/|title=Texas Woman Gives Birth to First Set of All-Girl Quintuplets in U.S.|work=KTLA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/texas-hospital-welcomes-girl-quintuplets-born-us/story?id=30314322|title=Texas Hospital Welcomes First All-Girl Quintuplets Ever Born in US|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}<