===Sextuplets (6)=== [[File:KoreAm 2008-05 Cover.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Kate Plus 8|Gosselin sextuplets]] with family on the cover of the May 2008 ''[[KoreAm]]'']] * The Thorns sextuplets (born October 2, 1968, in [[Birmingham]], [[England]]) were born to Sheila and Barry Thorns. They were the first sextuplets known to have been born alive in the United Kingdom, but one baby died shortly after birth, and another two died within the next two weeks.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/2/newsid_3107000/3107371.stm 1968: Birth of sextuplets stuns Britain]." (n.d.). ''[[On This Day]].'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=198013 Sextuplets/England]." (October 2, 1968). ''CBS Evening News.'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1968/10/14/archives/2d-of-the-sextuplets-is-dead-in-birmingham.html 2d of the Sextuplets Is Dead in Birmingham]." (October 14, 1968). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1968/10/23/archives/third-british-sextuplet-dies.html Third British Sextuplet Dies]." (October 23, 1968). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref> * The Letts sextuplets (born December 15, 1969, in London, England) were born to Rosemary and John Letts two months prematurely at [[University College Hospital]]. One boy and four girls survived, (Cara Dawn, Sharon Marie, Joanne Nadine, Gary John, and Tanya Odile) one female was stillborn. This was the second case of surviving quintuplets in the United Kingdom. The family immigrated to [[Canada]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19691216&id=l3wzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4DIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=4698,6930153|title=Lodi News-Sentinel - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19691216&id=USMrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RKAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5311,3560312|title=Reading Eagle - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19760224&id=Cd49AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HkgMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3213,4503753|title=The Glasgow Herald - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/highermultiples/worldsextuplets|title=World Sextuplets - World Higher Multiples|publisher=}}</ref> * The [[Rosenkowitz sextuplets]] (born January 11, 1974, in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]) were the first sextuplets known to survive their infancy.<ref>"[http://www.dispatch.co.za/2004/01/10/Editoria/chiel.html The Six Are 30] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515171207/http://www.dispatch.co.za/2004/01/10/editoria/chiel.html |date=2009-05-15 }}." (January 10, 2004). ''Dispatch.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> They were conceived using fertility drugs.<ref name="nytimes1974-1">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/01/12/archives/sextuplets-born-in-capetown-survival-chances-called-good.html?sq=Rosenkowitz&scp=2&st=cse | title=Sextuplets Born in Capetown; Survival Chances Called Good | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=Jan 12, 1974 | accessdate=Sep 21, 2009}}("Sextuplets have been born to a number of women who have taken (hormone fertility) drugs, and the largest number known to have survived are five of the six babies born in 1973 to Mrs. Edna Stanek of Denver.")</ref> * The Nijssen sextuplets (born September 21, 1977, in the [[Netherlands]]) were born to Corry and Sien Nijssen two months prematurely. There were four girls (Patricia, Priscilla, Mirella, and Ramona) and two boys (Ivo and Dennis). Dennis died on November 9, 1977. They are the only set in the Netherlands.<ref>"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,915546,00.html Milestones, Oct. 3, 1977]".</ref> * The [[Giannini sextuplets]] (born on January 11, 1980, in [[Italy]]) were the second sextuplets known to survive their infancy. They were born on the same date as the Rosenkowitz sextuplets, six years later.<ref>{{It icon}} Marongiu, Cinzia. (n.d.). "[http://www.sorrisi.com/sorrisi/upload/libro2004/tv/tv2005/quintuplets.pdf Siamo i gemelli più noti della tv] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927065614/http://www.sorrisi.com/sorrisi/upload/libro2004/tv/tv2005/quintuplets.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }}." ''[[TV Sorrisi e Canzoni]]''. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Vanhove Gadeyne sextuplets (born on August 17, 1983, in [[Blankenberge]], [[Belgium]]) were the first set of sextuplets to have been born in [[Belgium]]. The five boys (Bruno, Jelle, Tom, Lode, Arne) and one girl (Veerle) weighed between 2&nbsp;lbs 9oz and 3&nbsp;lbs 3oz at birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jLEvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=n_kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6930,819870&dq=belgium+sextuplets&hl=en|title=Spokane Chronicle - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref> * The [[Walton sextuplets]] (born on November 18, 1983, in [[Liverpool]]) were the first sextuplets born in the [[United Kingdom]] known to survive their infancy, and the world's first all-female sextuplets.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/1655526.stm Walton sextuplets come of age]." (November 14, 2001). ''BBC News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> They were delivered by [[Cesarian section]] at 31 and a half weeks.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/waltons-sextuplets-30-catching-up-3383409 The Waltons at 30: Catching up with the famous family as they return to the TV screen] Retrieved June 18, 2016.</ref> * The [[Dilley sextuplets]] (born on May 25, 1993, in [[Indianapolis]]) were the first surviving set of sextuplets in the United States. They are two girls (Brenna Rose and Claire Diane) and four boys (Julian Emerson, Quinn Everett, Ian Michael, and Adrian Reed).<ref name="dilley">[http://www.incrediblebirths.com/Dilley_Sextuplets_1993.html Dilley Sextuplets birth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617230727/http://www.incrediblebirths.com/Dilley_Sextuplets_1993.html |date=June 17, 2008 }}</ref> * The Boniello sextuplets (born March 24, 1997, in [[Stony Brook, New York]]) set a record for the longest [[gestation]] of a sextuplet pregnancy in the United States at 29 weeks and one day. They have a younger sister Nadia.<ref>Eltman, Frank. (April 6, 2007). "[http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/04/06/party_for_10_year_old_ny_sextuplets/ N.Y. sextuplets celebrate turning 10]." ''The Boston Globe.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> This record was broken almost two months later by the Thompson sextuplets. * The Thompson sextuplets (born May 8, 1997, in [[Washington, D.C.]]) were born to Jacqueline and Linden Thompson. Mrs. Thompson set a record for the longest sextuplet pregnancy in the United States at 29 weeks and six days. One girl was stillborn; the five survivors are four girls (Octavia Daniela, Stella Kimberly, Ann Marie Amanda, and Emily Elizabeth) and one boy (Richard Linden). They are the first African-American sextuplets. They each weighed between 2&nbsp;lbs 2oz and 2&nbsp;lbs 6oz.<ref>"{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_n2_v92/ai_19487235 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227182729/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_n2_v92/ai_19487235 |archivedate=2008-12-27 |df= }}." Retrieved December 9, 2008.</ref> * The Harris sextuplets (born July 7, 2002, in [[Alabama]]) are two girls (Kiera Christine and Kalynne Antoinett) and four boys (Kaleb Reddrick, Kobe Byshari, Kieran Anthony, and Kyle Jacob). They are Alabama's first set of sextuplets and were the first recorded set of surviving African-American sextuplets.<ref>"[http://multiples.about.com/gi/dynamic/offsite.htm?zi=1/XJ/Ya&sdn=multiples&cdn=parenting&tm=23&gps=419_666_1020_615&f=21&su=p284.8.150.ip_&tt=14&bt=1&bts=1&zu=http://www.harrissextuplets.net/home.shtml]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved January 27, 2008.</ref> Kaleb has nerve damage; while Kiera and Kyle are [[autistic]].<ref>http://blog.al.com/birmingham-news-stories/2009/11/harris_sextuplets_of_alabama_g.html Kaleb has slight nerve damage to his mouth, and Kiera and Kyle have autism</ref> The Harris family received a new home in a 2005 episode of ''[[Extreme Makeover: Home Edition]]''. The Harris' original three-bedroom, three-bath house was razed and a two-story, {{convert|5000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} home was built.<ref>http://www.harrissextuplets.net/extreme.shtml Extreme Makeover Pictures</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2010/11/harris_sextupulets_mayors_home.html|title=Harris sextuplets, mayor's homes up for preservation group's tour|work=AL.com}}</ref> * The [[Kate Plus 8|Gosselin sextuplets]] (born May 10, 2004, in [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]]) were born just shy of 30 weeks gestation to parents Jon and Kate Gosselin. The set has three girls (Alexis Faith, Hannah Joy, and Leah Hope) and three boys (Aaden Jonathan, Collin Thomas, Joel Kevin). The parents also have twin girls, Madelyn Kate and Cara Nicole, who were three years old at the time of the sextuplets' birth.<ref>Farr, Gary. (May 10, 2004). "[http://www.becomehealthynow.com/article/womenpreg/1156/?hub=Woman Gives Birth To Sextuplets] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929080923/http://www.becomehealthynow.com/article/womenpreg/1156/?hub=Woman |date=September 29, 2007 }}." Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.wgal.com/family/4463033/detail.html [[Jon & Kate Plus 8|Gosselin Sextuplets]] To Turn 1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517093347/http://www.wgal.com/family/4463033/detail.html |date=2007-05-17 }}." (May 7, 2005). ''WGAL.com''. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> The family was the subject of a reality television show, originally titled ''Jon & Kate Plus 8'', that aired on [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] in the United States and Canada. The show was initially canceled after Jon and Kate's divorce, but was revived as ''[[Kate Plus 8]]'' after viewer complaints. The series ended in 2011, with the last episode airing on September 12 of that year, then resumed with a new season in January 2015. * The Hayes sextuplets (born September 14, 2004, in [[Long Branch, New Jersey]]) are the first surviving sextuplets to be born in [[New Jersey]]. The six children, three boys (Ryan Peter, Connor James, Eric John) and three girls (Tara Rose, Rachel Ann, Rebecca Mary), weighed a total of 24&nbsp;lbs. and 14 oz., setting a world record for the heaviest set of sextuplets. The Hayes also have two sets of twins, Kevin and Kyle (eight years old at the time of the sextuplets' birth) and Kieran and Meghan (five years old). They are the only family in the United States to have two sets of twins and a set of sextuplets.<ref>DeNicola, Linda. (September 21, 2004). "[http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2004/0921/Front_Page/027.html Police officer and wife celebrating sextuplet] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703114102/http://newstranscript.gmnews.com/news/2004/0921/Front_Page/027.html |date=July 3, 2007 }}." ''News Transcript.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> The family were the subject of a reality television show, ''[[Table for 12]]'', on [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] in the U.S.<ref>Lafayette, Jon. (March 8, 2009). "[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2009/03/tlc_adds_to_its_tv_family.php TLC Adds to Its TV Family: ‘Table for 12’ Joins Big-Brood Lineup]." ''TVWeek.'' Retrieved March 20, 2009.</ref> * [[Canada]]'s first sextuplets (born January 6–7, 2007 in [[Vancouver]]) were born at 25 weeks gestation. Two of them died shortly after birth.<ref>"[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070107/bc_sextuplets_070108/20070108?hub=Canada Woman gives birth to sextuplets at B.C. hospital]." (January 8, 2007). ''CTV.ca.'' Retrieved March 2, 2007.</ref><ref>"[[n:Sextuplets born in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada|Sextuplets born in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada]]." (January 8, 2007). ''Wikinews.'' Retrieved March 2, 2007.</ref> * The Carpio sextuplets (born October 6, 2008, in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Queens]]) are the first Hispanic sextuplets to be born in America. It is not known if their parents, Victor and Digna Carpio, conceived using fertility treatments. The babies (Justin, Jadon, Jezreel, Danelia, Genesis, and Joel) were delivered by Caesarean section at 25 weeks.<ref>"[http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/queens/2008/10/26/2008-10-26_secret_of_their_6cess_queens_couple_vict.html Secret of their 6-cess: Queens couple Victor and Digna Carpio share story delivery of sextuplets]".</ref> They were the subject of a reality television show, [[Sextuplets Take New York|''Sextuplets Take New York'']]. * The Conway sextuplets (born on May 22, 2009) in Dunmore in County Tyrone, Northern Ireland were the first recorded sextuplets in Ireland. The four girls and two boys weighed between 1&nbsp;lb., 7 oz. and 2&nbsp;lb., 2 oz. were fourteen weeks premature and were named Ursula, Shannon, Karla, Kerrie (died July 20, 2009), Austin and Eoghan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://multiples.about.com/od/quintssextuplets/p/conwaysextuplets.htm|title=Conway Sextuplets - Profile of Conway Family Sextuplets - Irish Sextuplets|author=Pamela Prindle Fierro|work=About.com Health}}</ref> * On March 4, 2013, the first sextuplets in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] and the [[Caribbean]] were born at the Maternity Hospital of the Eric Williams Medical Sciences Complex at Mount Hope, Trinidad and Tobago to an anonymous Trinidadian couple. Two of them died a few weeks later.<ref>"http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Second-sextuplet-dies-203515681.html"</ref><ref>"http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Region_s_first_sextuplets_due_next_month-190308901.html"</ref><ref>"http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/SIX_IN_ONE_SHOT-195197121.html"</ref><ref>"http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,174381.html"</ref>
===Septuplets (7)=== * The Frustaci septuplets (born May 21, 1985, in [[Orange, California]]) were the first septuplets to be born in the [[United States of America|United States]]. Born at 28 weeks, only two boys and one girl survived; one daughter was stillborn and three died within 19 days of birth.<ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9711/20/septuplets.frustaci/index.html#1 Septuplets heartache: the Frustaci story] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630094042/http://www.cnn.com/US/9711/20/septuplets.frustaci/index.html |date=June 30, 2007 }}." (November 20, 1997). ''CNN.com''. Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The [[McCaughey septuplets]] (born November 19, 1997, in [[Des Moines, Iowa]]) were the world's first surviving set of septuplets. The four boys (Kenneth Jr., Brandon, Nathan, and Joel) and three girls (Alexis, Natalie, and Kelsey) were born at 31 weeks, weighing between 2&nbsp;lbs. 5&nbsp;oz. and 3&nbsp;lbs 4&nbsp;oz.<ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9711/19/septuplets.2nd.wrap/index.html Septuplets survive 'miracle' birth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123000927/http://www.cnn.com/US/9711/19/septuplets.2nd.wrap/index.html |date=November 23, 2007 }}." (November 19, 1997). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9712/10/briefs.pm/septuplets/index.html?iref=newssearch McCaughey septuplets get an agent]." (December 10, 1997). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9811/18/septuplets.01/ McCaughey septuplets turn 1] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020122712/http://www.cnn.com/US/9811/18/septuplets.01/ |date=October 20, 2007 }}." (November 18, 1998). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> In 2016, they became the first set of septuplets to reach maturity. * The Humair septuplets (born January 14, 1998, in [[Abha]], [[Saudi Arabia]]) were the world's second surviving set of septuplets. They were born at 32 weeks to 40-year-old Hasna Mohammed Humair and her husband, Abdullah Mohammed Ali. They had been told to expect four babies.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/despatches/61129.stm Saudi septuplets cause hospital bed shortage]." (March 1, 1998). ''BBC News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://www.hannibal.net/stories/030698/septuplets.html Mother of Saudi septuplets reaches pact with hospital] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928103237/http://www.hannibal.net/stories/030698/septuplets.html |date=September 28, 2007 }}." (March 6, 1998). ''Hannibal Courier-Post.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref name="octuplets1">"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9812/22/octuplets.02/index.html?iref=newssearch Doctor optimistic about octuplets]." (December 22, 1998). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The Qahtani septuplets (born July 12, 2001, in [[Washington, D.C.]]) are the third set of septuplets to live past infancy.<ref>Hodge, Georgina. (July 17, 2001). "[http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/07/17/story8082.asp Father of septuplets thanks God for new arrivals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929152635/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/07/17/story8082.asp |date=September 29, 2007 }}." ''Irish Examiner.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>Stolberg, Sheryl Gay. (July 14, 2001). "[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9A05E3DB123BF937A25754C0A9679C8B63 Septuplets Born in Capital Are Third Set in the World]." ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://archives.cnn.com/2001/HEALTH/parenting/07/16/septuplets.condition/index.html Septuplets given '95 percent' chance] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014174148/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/HEALTH/parenting/07/16/septuplets.condition/index.html |date=October 14, 2007 }}." (July 16, 2001). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> In December 2001, it was reported that one of the septuplets had died of liver failure and three were still hospitalized.<ref>"[http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=11534&d=26&m=12&y=2001&pix=kingdom.jpg&category=Kingdom One of Qahtani septuplets dies]." (December 26, 2001). ''Arab News.'' Retrieved February 15, 2009.</ref> * A set of septuplets were born on April 18, 2007, in a suburb of [[Algiers]], [[Algeria]] to Farhat and Souhila Touile. One of the babies, a boy, was stillborn; the remaining six are girls.<ref>"[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007/04/23/story_23-4-2007_pg6_8 Algerian woman gives birth to septuplets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930191828/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%2F04%2F23%2Fstory_23-4-2007_pg6_8 |date=September 30, 2007 }}." (April 23, 2007). ''Daily Times.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://news.monstersandcritics.com/africa/news/article_1293537.php/Algerian_woman_gives_birth_to_septuplets Algerian woman gives birth to septuplets] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070614214840/http://news.monstersandcritics.com/africa/news/article_1293537.php/Algerian_woman_gives_birth_to_septuplets |date=June 14, 2007 }}." (April 19, 2007). ''Monsters and Critics.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>{{Sp icon}}" [http://elmundosalud.elmundo.es/elmundosalud/2007/04/19/mujer/1177003591.html Una mujer argelina da a luz a siete bebés]." (April 20, 2007). ''El Mundo.'' Retrieved November 13, 2007.</ref> * The Khamis septuplets (born August 16, 2008, in [[Alexandria, Egypt]]) were born to 27-year-old Ghazala Khamis. They were the fifth set of septuplets to all survive. The newborns, four boys and three girls, had been placed in incubators in four different hospitals since they were premature. The babies' weights ranged from {{convert|1.45|to|2.8|kg|lb}}. The mother took fertility drugs in order to produce a son, since she already had three daughters.<ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/HEALTH/08/16/egypt.septuplets.birth.ap/?iref=hpmostpop www.cnn.com Egyptian woman gives birth to septuplets]{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}." Retrieved August 16, 2008.</ref><ref>"[http://www.kansascity.com/450/story/751461.html www.kansascity.com Hospital: Egyptian woman gives birth to septuplets]." Retrieved August 16, 2008.</ref> * The McGhee septuplets (born June 9, 2010, in [[Columbus, Ohio]]) were born to Mia and Rozonno McGhee at 27 weeks. One girl was stillborn. The other two girls (Olivia and Madison) and the four boys (Rozonno Jr., Elijah, Isaac, and Josiah) weighed between 1.5&nbsp;lb. to a fraction over 2&nbsp;lbs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.10tv.com/live/content/local/stories/2010/06/09/story-columbus-sextuplets-born-ohio-state-university-medical-center.html?sid=102 |title=First Set Of Sextuplets Born At OSU Medical Center |work=WBNS-10TV Columbus, Ohio |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103011416/http://www.10tv.com/live/content/local/stories/2010/06/09/story-columbus-sextuplets-born-ohio-state-university-medical-center.html?sid=102 |archivedate=2010-11-03 |df= }}</ref><ref>"{{cite web|url=http://www2.nbc4i.com/news/2010/jun/09/3/sextuplets-born-osu-medical-center-ar-103096/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724061125/http://www2.nbc4i.com/news/2010/jun/09/3/sextuplets-born-osu-medical-center-ar-103096/ |archivedate=2011-07-24 |df= }}." Retrieved June 9, 2010.</ref>
===Octuplets (8)=== * The first confirmed birth of octuplets occurred on March 10, 1967, in [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]] to Maria Teresa López de Sepulveda. All four boys and four girls died within 13 hours.<ref>"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,836829,00.html Trillion-to-One Chance]." (Mar. 17, 1967). ''Time.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1967/03/11/archives/octuplets-born-in-mexico-city-4-die-hope-for-others-is-slim.html Octuplets Born in Mexico City]." (March 11, 1967). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1967/03/12/archives/last-of-octuplets-is-dead-in-mexico-4-boys-and-4-girls-were-born.html Last of Octuplets Dead in Mexico]." (March 12, 1967). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref> * A set of octuplets were born on August 16, 1979, to Pasqualina and Stefano Chianese in [[Naples]], [[Italy]]. Six of the babies died and two survived. The couple had previously lost a set of sextuplets in 1976.<ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/17/archives/italian-woman-gives-birth-to-8-but-one-dies.html Italian Woman Gives Birth to 8, but one Dies]." (August 17, 1979). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1979/11/04/archives/italian-octuplet-goes-home.html Italian Octuplet Goes Home]." (November 4, 1979). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=61166 Italy/Octuplets]." (August 16, 1979). ''ABC Evening News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=61186 Italy/Octuplets]." (August 17, 1979). ''ABC Evening News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=506093 Italy/Octuplets]." (August 30, 1979). ''NBC Evening News.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * A set of octuplets were born on December 20, 1985, to Sevil Capan of [[İzmir]], Turkey. Born prematurely at 28 weeks, six of the octuplets died within 12 hours of birth, and the remaining two died within three days.<ref name="octuplets1" /><ref>Babineck, Mark. (December 21, 1998). "[http://www.texnews.com/1998/texas/oct1221.html Woman gives birth to first known surviving octuplets] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927015450/http://www.texnews.com/1998/texas/oct1221.html |date=September 27, 2007 }}." ''Abilene Reporter-News.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref> * A set of octuplets were born between September 30 and October 2, 1996, in a hospital in [[South London]], [[United Kingdom]] to Mandy Allwood of [[Solihull]]. Allwood was only 19 weeks pregnant when she went into pre-term labor with her six boys (Adam, Cassius, Donald, Kypros, Martyn, and Nelson) and two girls (Layne and Kitali). None of her octuplets survived.<ref>Hall, Celia & King, Tim. (October 3, 1996). "[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/1996/10/03/nman03.html Mandy Allwood loses all eight of her babies]." ''The Daily Telegraph.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref> She had refused [[selective reduction]] and her case provoked a media storm in the UK. * A set of octuplets were born on December 5, 1996, in [[Huelva]], [[Spain]] to Rosario Clavijo. Two of them were stillborn and six survived.<ref name="octuplets1" /><ref>"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E1DE173FF935A35751C1A960958260&n=Top%2fNews%2fHealth%2fDiseases%2c%20Conditions%2c%20and%20Health%20Topics%2fMultiple%20Births Spanish Sextuplets Born 10 Weeks Early]." (December 6, 1996). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * The [[Chukwu octuplets]] were born in December 1998 in [[Houston, Texas]], [[United States]]. The smallest of the octuplets, Odera, died a week after birth.<ref>"[http://www.cnn.com/US/9901/01/octuplets/ Chukwu octuplets greet new year in critical but stable condition]." (January 1, 1999). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * A set of octuplets were born between September 13 and September 16, 2000, in [[Milan]], Italy to Mariella Mazzara and Giovanni Pierrera of [[Trapani]]. One died immediately after birth, two within a few days of birth, and the oldest, Margherita, died a month later on October 10.<ref>"[http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/europe/09/17/italy.babies/ Sicilian mother gives birth to octuplets] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123014352/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/europe/09/17/italy.babies/ |date=November 23, 2007 }}." (September 17, 2000). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref><ref>"[http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/europe/italy/10/10/octuplets/index.html First born octuplet is fourth to die] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071004232653/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/europe/italy/10/10/octuplets/index.html |date=October 4, 2007 }}." (October 10, 2000). ''CNN.com.'' Retrieved June 29, 2007.</ref> * On January 26, 2009, the [[Suleman octuplets]] were born in [[Bellflower, California]], [[United States]].<ref name="bbc">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7852623.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Americas - US woman gives birth to octuplets|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="latimes">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2009/01/a-mother-has-gi.html|title=Octuplets born in Bellflower [UPDATED]|publisher=}}</ref> One week after birth, the Suleman octuplets became the longest-living octuplets in known history.<ref name="zrf">[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2009/01/30/national/a214200S49.DTL&tsp=1 Octuplets mom gets TV, book offers to tell story], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', February 2, 2009 {{dead link|date=May 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The children's names are Noah, Maliyah, Isaiah, Nariyah, Makai, Josiah, Jeremiah and Jonah. They were conceived through [[In vitro fertilisation|IVF]]. They have six older siblings, including a set of fraternal twins. They are the first octuplets known to survive their infancy.<ref>[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/01/octomom-octuplets-birthday-nadya-suleman.html 'Octomom' Nadya Suleman's octuplets celebrate 3rd birthday], By Alan Zarembo, January 26, 2012, Los Angeles Times</ref>
===Nonuplets (9)=== * A set of nonuplets were born on June 13, 1971, in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] to Geraldine Brodrick. They were five boys and four girls; two of the boys were stillborn<ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1971/06/13/archives/australian-woman-gives-birth-to-nine-seven-of-them-alive.html Australian Woman Gives Birth to Nine, Seven of Them Alive]." (June 13, 1971). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref> and the last of the babies died six days after birth.<ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1971/06/14/archives/4-still-survive-in-birth-of-9.html 4 Still Survive in Birth of 9]." (June 14, 1971). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref><ref>"[https://www.nytimes.com/1971/06/20/archives/last-of-the-nonuplets-dies-at-sydney-hospital.html Last of the Nonuplets Dies at Sydney Hospital]." (June 20, 1971). ''The New York Times.'' Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref> * A set of nonuplets were born on March 26, 1999, in [[Malaysia]] to Zurina Mat Saad. She had five boys and four girls (Adam, Nuh, Idris, Soleh, Hud, Aishah, Khadijah, Fatimah, and Umi Kalsom), but none of them survived more than 6 hours.<ref>Pinchuk, Stacey. (2000).[http://www.law.duke.edu/shell/cite.pl?7+Duke+J.+Gender+L.+&+Pol'y+29#F4 A Difficult Choice in a Different Voice: Multiple Births, Selective Reduction and Abortion]. ''Duke Journal of Gender Law & Policy, 7,'' p. 29. Retrieved June 30, 2007.</ref>
